ce:section.ce:para:
In the plant hormone signal transduction, each hormone triggers a specific molecular pathway, which interacts in a complex network with synergistic, antagonistic, and additive interactions, known as hormonal crosstalk (Aerts, Pereira Mendes, & Van Wees, 2021). These hormones act as signaling molecules by binding to specific receptors, amplifying and delivering signaling substances within the cell (Waadt et al., 2022). Wu et al (Wu, Ge, et al., 2023). demonstrated that IMI stress can inhibit plant hormone signal transduction, particularly auxin (IAA)-mediated signaling. Current studies have suggested that 56 DEGs were involved in 8 plant hormone signals pathways, including IAA, ethylene (ETH), abscisic acid (ABA), cytokinin (CTK), jasmonic acid (JA), gibberellic acid (GA), brassinosteroid (BR), and salicylic acid (SA) pathways. Under IMI conditions, CDs treatment significantly activated all pathways except BR and SA (
                        Fig. 6

                        ). Additionally, Additionally, receptor genes for these hormones, such as LsTIR1, LsETR1, LsPYP/PYL1, LsCRE, LsCOI1, LsGID1, LsBIR1, and LsNPR1, exhibited notable upregulation by CDs treatment. Conversely, receptors like LsCRE, LsBIR1, and LsNPR1 showed downregulation (
                        Fig. 6
                        ) (genes information in Table S6). This receptor modulation by CDs may facilitate signal transmission and transmembrane transport, thus enhancing hormonal crosstalk. Therefore, this upregulation of hormone receptors by CDs mitigates the inhibitory effects of IMI stress on hormonal signal transduction. This mechanism highlights how CDs may bolster plant defense responses to environmental stress by enhancing hormone-mediated signaling pathways.
